Package io.github.ai4ci.config.execution

Interface ExecutionConfiguration

All Superinterfaces:
Abstraction.Named, Abstraction.Replica, DemographicAdjustment.Execution<Distribution,Double>, Serializable
@Immutable public interface ExecutionConfiguration extends Abstraction.Named, Abstraction.Replica, Serializable, DemographicAdjustment.Execution<Distribution,Double>
Central configuration for executing epidemiological Agent-Based Model simulations.

Controls all aspects of ABM execution including:

  • Disease transmission parameters (R0, progression rates)
  • Contact patterns and mobility
  • Intervention policies (testing, lockdowns)
  • Behavioral responses by individuals
  • Within-host disease progression

The configuration influences both:

  • Population-level dynamics (through policies and global parameters)
  • Individual behaviors (through contact patterns, compliance, testing)

Example usage: 


 ExecutionConfiguration config = ExecutionConfiguration.DEFAULT
 		.withReplicate(1).withName("scenario1");
Author:
Rob Challen

  • Field Details

    • DEFAULT

      static final io.github.ai4ci.config.execution.ImmutableExecutionConfiguration DEFAULT
      Default immutable configuration instance with baseline epidemiological parameters.

      This configuration provides reasonable defaults for:

      • Transmission (R0=1.75)
      • Disease severity (5% hospitalisation, 1% fatality)
      • Testing (1% screening probability)
      • Contact patterns (50% baseline contact probability)
      • Behaviour models (ReactiveTestAndIsolate)
      • Policy models (ReactiveLockdown)

      Population-level impacts:

      • Defines baseline transmission potential
      • Sets lockdown triggers (5% positivity to start, 1% to release)
      • Configures default testing parameters

      Individual-level impacts:

      • Sets baseline contact probabilities
      • Configures symptom reporting behavior
      • Defines compliance rates (99% baseline)

    • getAppUseProbability

      Distribution getAppUseProbability()
      How likely was it that a person uses a contact tracing app? This distribution is sampled from for each person in the network to set their baseline probability of using a contact tracing app PersonBaseline.getAppUseProbability(). This parameter is important for modelling the effectiveness of digital contact tracing interventions, as higher app usage can lead to more effective identification and isolation of contacts, thereby reducing transmission. Adjusting this parameter allows for exploration of different scenarios regarding public adoption of contact tracing technologies.

      Individual-level impact (PersonBaseline)

    • getComplianceDeteriorationRate

      Double getComplianceDeteriorationRate()
      The absolute rate of decrease in compliance in situations where the person is asked to self isolate. This is used direction by the behaviour models (via StateUtils) to determine how quickly an individual's compliance with isolation and other guidance deteriorates over time when they are asked to self isolate or are otherwise forced to do something. This parameter captures the phenomenon of "compliance fatigue". Although this is set across the whole population it is applied at the individual level and modifies an individual compliance probability that is set.

      Population-level impact (BehaviourModel)

      Returns:
      Absolute rate of compliance deterioration (e.g., 0.02 per day)
      See Also:
      • StateUtils.complianceFatigue(io.github.ai4ci.abm.ImmutablePersonState.Builder, io.github.ai4ci.abm.PersonState)

    • getContactProbability

      Distribution getContactProbability()
      The proportion of a persons social network that they see each day in a fully mobile population. The mobility baseline is determined from this but as the contact is the product of 2 peoples mobility the average probability of a contact will be the square of the central value. In the case of a Watts-Strogatz or similar social network setting this to be a uniform distribution is recommended to get an approximate scale free contact distribution. PersonBaseline.getMobilityBaseline()

      Individual-level impact (PersonBaseline):

      • Used to determine each person's baseline mobility
      • Directly affects transmission probability between agents
      Specified by:
      getContactProbability in interface DemographicAdjustment.Execution<Distribution,Double>
      Returns:
      Probability distribution (typically unimodal beta)

    • getDemographicAdjustment

      io.github.ai4ci.config.execution.PartialDemographicAdjustment getDemographicAdjustment()
      Adjustment of different parameters as a function of age or other demographics. In general this specifies either single valued functions or probabilistic adjustments to parameters based on demographic characteristics. These adjustments are applied to the baseline parameters defined in this configuration to create demographic-specific parameters for individuals in the population. For example, if the case fatality rate is 1% in the baseline configuration and the demographic adjustment specifies an odds ratio of 2 for a certain age group, then the adjusted case fatality rate for that age group would be approximately 2%.

      The exact method of adjustment depends on the type of parameter: probabilistic parameters will be adjusted as an odds ratio and other real values quantities will be simply scaled by the adjustment value. Adjustments are matched to their parameters by name and this is performed by ReflectionUtils.modify(X, PartialDemographicAdjustment, PersonDemographic).

      At the moment this is only defined for age but it could be extended to other demographics such as location, socioeconomic status, or comorbidities however multivariate distributions would be needed to capture interactions between demographics.

      Individual-level impact (PersonBaseline)

      Returns:
      PartialDemographicAdjustment instance defining how parameters are adjusted based on demographics.
      See Also:
      • DemographicAdjustment.Execution
      • DemographicAdjustment.Phenomenological
      • DemographicAdjustment.Markov

      Double getImportationProbability()
      This defines the probability of and individual with standard mobility being infected from outside the simulated population per time step. This will create a random exposure uniform across the population depending on individual mobility. This feature is experimental and may be revised or removed in future versions. It is likely that it will be replaced with temporal functions.
      Returns:
      Probability of external infection per time step for a fully mobile individual (e.g., 0.001)

      InHostConfiguration getInHostConfiguration()
      Gets the within-host disease progression configuration. The configuration defines the model used for simulating viral load dynamics, symptom onset, and disease severity in infected individuals.

      Options include phenomenological models (e.g. viral load profiles based on empirical data) mechanistic Markov models of disease progression, and mechanistic stochastic compartment models.

    • getMaximumSocialContactReduction

      Distribution getMaximumSocialContactReduction()
      Each individual has a personal maximum that their social contact can be reduced by PersonBaseline.getSelfIsolationDepth(), which is sampled from this distribution. This in turn is used by the behaviour models to limit the maximum reduction in contact that an individual can achieve when they are asked to self isolate (via StateUtils).

      Individual-level impact (PersonBaseline):

      • Determines the maximum possible reduction in social contacts for each agent
      • Limits the effectiveness of self-isolation and other contact-reducing behaviors
      Specified by:
      getMaximumSocialContactReduction in interface DemographicAdjustment.Execution<Distribution,Double>
      Returns:
      Distribution representing the population-level variability in maximum social contact reduction (e.g., unimodal beta distribution with mean around 0.25 to reflect that most people can reduce contacts by about 75% at most)

    • getR0

      Double getR0()
      Gets the basic reproduction number (R0) for the disease. This is used by the calibration in conjunction with the contact probability, the viral load profile from getViralLoadProfile(), and the network structure to calibrate the baseline per contact transmission parameter. This is in turn used to produce per contact transmission probability based on the in host viral load of the infected individual and the contact probabilities of the infected and susceptible individual.
      Returns:
      Average number of secondary cases from one infected individual
      See Also:
      • getContactProbability()

    • getRiskModelContactsKernel

      KernelFunction getRiskModelContactsKernel()
      Gets the kernel function for contact based risk assessment in the RiskModel. This kernel defines how the presence and timing of contacts with people who are themselves at risk of being infectious contribute to an individual's perceived risk of being infectious. This can be expressed as a GaussianKernel, EmpiricalKernel or DiscreteFunction depending on the desired shape of the risk contribution over time.
      Returns:
      KernelFunction defining the temporal risk contribution of contacts in the RiskModel.

    • getRiskModelSymptomKernel

      KernelFunction getRiskModelSymptomKernel()
      Gets the kernel function for symptom-based risk assessment in the RiskModel. This kernel defines how the presence and timing of symptoms contribute to an individual's perceived risk of being infectious given symptoms. This can be expressed as a GaussianKernel, EmpiricalKernel or DiscreteFunction depending on the desired shape of the risk contribution over time.
      Returns:
      KernelFunction defining the temporal risk contribution of symptoms in the RiskModel.

    • getRiskModelTestKernel

      KernelFunction getRiskModelTestKernel()
      Gets the kernel function for test results based risk assessment in the RiskModel. This kernel defines how the presence and timing of test results contribute to an individual's perceived risk of being infectious given a positive test result. This can be expressed as a GaussianKernel, EmpiricalKernel or DiscreteFunction depending on the desired shape of the risk contribution over time.
      Returns:
      KernelFunction defining the temporal risk contribution of test results in the RiskModel.

    • getSymptomSensitivity

      Distribution getSymptomSensitivity()
      Gets the sensitivity of symptom-based detection. This parameter defines the probability at a population level that infected individuals will experience symptoms when they have disease PersonBaseline.getSymptomSensitivity(). This is sampled for each individual to determine their baseline personal symptom sensitivity, which in turn affects the likelihood of symptom onset.

      Individual-level impact (PersonBaseline):

      • Determines the likelihood of symptom onset in infected agents
      • Affects the effectiveness of symptom-based interventions (e.g., self-isolation, testing)
      Returns:
      A probability distribution representing the population-level symptom sensitivity (e.g., unimodal beta distribution)

    • getSymptomSpecificity

      Distribution getSymptomSpecificity()
      Gets the specificity of symptom-based detection. The complement of this parameter defines the probability at a population level that uninfected individuals will experience symptoms that are mistaken for disease PersonBaseline.getSymptomSpecificity(). This is sampled for each individual to determine their baseline personal symptom specificity, which in turn affects the baseline likelihood of false symptom onset.

      Individual-level impact (PersonBaseline):

      • Determines the likelihood of false symptom onset in uninfected agents
      • Affects the rate of false positives in symptom-based interventions
      Returns:
      A probability distribution representing the population-level symptom specificity (e.g., unimodal beta distribution)

    • getViralLoadProfile

      @Lazy default double[][] getViralLoadProfile()
      For a configuration gets a set of viral load profiles from an average set of participants. The profiles are generated from the in-host model defined in the configuration and are used by the calibration to calibrate the transmission parameter to achieve the desired R0.

      Each profile is a time series of viral load values that represent the infectiousness of an individual over time after infection. The profiles are typically generated for a fixed number of time steps (e.g., 100) and can be used to determine the temporal dynamics of transmission in the model.

      Because they undergo further transformation during calibration to produce the final transmission profile, they cannot be averaged at this stage (unlike getSeverityProfile()) but they are generated from the same in-host model and parameters defined in the configuration to ensure consistency with the disease progression assumptions.

      Returns:
      2D array of viral load profiles (time steps x number of profiles)
